<p><b>Aldous Leonard Huxley</b> (26 July 1894&#160;– 22 November 1963) was an English writer and one of the most prominent members of the famous <a href="/wiki/Huxley_family" title="Huxley family">Huxley family</a>. He spent the later part of his life in the United States, living in Los Angeles from 1937 until his death in 1963. Best known for his <a href="/wiki/Novel" title="Novel">novels</a> and wide-ranging output of <a href="/wiki/Essay" title="Essay">essays</a>, he also published <a href="/wiki/Short_stories" title="Short stories" class="mw-redirect">short stories</a>, <a href="/wiki/Poetry" title="Poetry">poetry</a>, <a href="/wiki/Travel_writing" title="Travel writing">travel writing</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Film" title="Film">film</a> stories and scripts.</p>
<p>Huxley was a <a href="/wiki/Humanist" title="Humanist">humanist</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pacifist" title="Pacifist" class="mw-redirect">pacifist</a>, but was also latterly interested in spiritual subjects such as <a href="/wiki/Parapsychology" title="Parapsychology">parapsychology</a> and <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosophical</a> <a href="/wiki/Mysticism" title="Mysticism">mysticism</a>. He was also well known for advocating and taking <a href="/wiki/Psychedelic_drug" title="Psychedelic drug">psychedelics</a>.</p>
<p>By the end of his life Huxley was considered, in some academic circles, a leader of modern thought and an intellectual of the highest rank.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
